< review>
Very professional when I called about a rate increase due to an accident claim. Prior to my call, they had already taken initiative to optimize some details on my policy to lower my rate without changing my coverage.

They then put me in touch with someone from claims to get more information about my accident. Based on my poor initial description of the accident, claims had found we were at fault but after they asked me to clarify, they determined we were not at fault and changed the claim from collision to comprehensive and avoided the rate increase.

They were very polite and explained all my questions.<//review>

< Review>
FIRST TIME BUYER - - To whomever is considering doing business with Mr. Dan Patty...do your self a favor and partner with him, you will not regret it! This man is on top of it! Quick responses, complete and concise answers, no BS, very knowledgeable, and very patient! Most of all, he will certainly sniff out the best possible deals for you. To other first time buyers, do yourself another favor and go with a broker, not a lender! They can typically get you much better rates than a standard lender because they have a large pool of nationwide lenders they pull from for your specific situation. Thankfully, a family member of mine steered me toward Dan because they too had a great experience with him. I was particularly impressed with how low Dan was able to get my "PMI" or Premium Mortgage Insurance. This is typically something you pay if you are putting less than 20% down and the fee eventually goes away. Some PMI fees can be hundreds of dollars if you go with a lender or just get a bad deal. Dan was able to get mine down to just 30 something bucks. Thanks to Dan, I was able to afford more house as a single man than I ever could have imagined when I first set out looking for homes. Hell, this man even promptly returned my message when he was on vacation. He is very technology savvy and is very approachable. Like most things, the hardest part of the process for me was just taking that first step and getting the ball rolling on getting pre-approved for a loan amount. He makes it easy to get started and what he sends you along the way is not overwhelming, but rather very helpful and simple. The home buying process can be inherently stressful, but Dan mitigates that feeling of stress by keeping it simple, professional, and smooth. He didn't know my realtor at all and I received several compliments from my realtor about Dan and how well they worked together. Go with Dan!< /Review>

<userid>114796471539334312173< /userid>< Review>
My wife and I had the privilege of refinancing our home loan with Dan, but the thing that stood out the most to us was Dan's persistence.  We worked with Dan starting almost two years ago to pre-qualify and map out a plan to re-enter home ownership after suffering a foreclosure (business choice) during the market crash in 2008.  Dan helped us identify areas we could improve on, and advised us of what people in our situation would have to overcome.  We stuck to the plan and were able to get pre-qualified very quickly through Dan.

We kept our eyes on the market, thought about pulling the trigger a couple of times on an offer, but then had the opportunity to purchase our family home from my parents if we could wait a few years.  We told Dan of the plan and he never once seemed discouraged to have worked on our behalf without a deal being done.  He actually helped us identify favorable opportunities that exist when purchasing directly from family (no need for a realtor, possibility of a gift of equity, inheriting the original property taxes, etc.).

As we worked towards the goal of buying our family home Dan continued to work with us and was able to offer us a reasonable loan at the time we were ready to purchase, however after shopping around, specifically through Costco's mortgage program, we were able to get a more favorable loan.  Having developed a friendship with Dan through the years I was nervous about breaking the news to him that all of his work on behalf of my family was not going to conclude with a mortgage deal, but after breaking the news to Dan he said "Mike I completely understand, this is business and you have to do what's best for your family.  This is the best I can do with the options available to me, so please think of me in the future if you are ever in the market again."

Who the hell has that understanding and long term focus?  Dan.

Fast forward to six months after we purchased our family home with the Costco loan and I get an email from Dan explaining that he is his own boss now and that with that authority and an even lower interest rate than was available at the time of our purchase that he believed he could refinance our loan and save us money.

This dude!

Seriously, after working for years and getting nothing from us, he sought us out and offered to help us.  We took him up on the offer and just as he had predicted, Dan was able to shave a full percentage point off of our APR and close to $500 on our monthly bill.

We can't thank Dan enough for his amazing persistence, professionalism, and awareness of client's needs.  We will always shop Dan first, and we strongly encourage anyone in the market to do the same.  Dan Patty walks the walk in an industry known for being full of talkers.<//Review>

The crust is thin with a nice pillow-y edge. The sauce is very subtle (and I like that) and the cheese is melted evenly. The pizza was hella greasy (I like that too). 0x80dd310f283b8a79:0x555fc4cf7d59ce02</gmap_id>
< Review>
Great skates, but don't order them online directly from their website - go through amazon or something. I never post reviews about anything ever but I felt this needed to be said. This whole experience left a bad taste in my mouth and makes me not even want to skate anymore.

I pre-ordered the green (honeydew) color on June 12th and assumed they would ship when the skates officially released (June 14th I think), because that's how pre-orders are supposed to work. I also ordered a set of trick wheels on or around June 16th.

The confirmation e-mail they send when you place an order says "it takes 2-3 business days to process your order once it has been placed and 2 days to ship," unless they're out of stock, then they'll notify you. The e-mail also says the skates can take 1-5 weeks to make if they're not it stock. I assumed I wouldn't have to deal with any of that because, again, I placed a pre-order.

On June 26th, 2 WEEKS after not hearing anything, I e-mailed them and asked if there were any updates. After e-mailing several times, I didn't get a response until July 2nd (a week later), and was told that if I ordered after April 1st the skates would ship out in the order they were purchased... That's doesn't sound like a pre-order to me.

On July 18th I was done waiting and proceeded to cancel my orders (both the trick wheels and the skates). I would order a different color through amazon instead. The trick wheel order was canceled the same day, the skates were not.

I e-mailed again on July 20th asking them to cancel my skate order. July 25th, I WAS TOLD MY SKATES HAD ALREADY SHIPPED AND THEY COULDN'T CANCEL THE ORDER. What!? That really pissed me off - you can cancel the wheels the same day but you wait until it's too late to cancel the skates? I honestly feel like they stole my money.

I finally received my skates on July 27th.

TL;DR - IT TOOK ME OVER 6 WEEKS TO GET MY SKATES, EVEN THOUGH I PRE-ORDERED THEM. Their customer service is sporadic at best - sometimes I would get an e-mail back the same day and other times weeks later - which ended up costing me hundreds of dollars for an extra pair of skates that I now have to send back to amazon (which I received in less than a week btw, shout out to amazon).

Thank you for reading, I hope this review helps someone.

edit: I'm sorry, but for the sake of visibility, I cannot remove this review. The online shop and physical store are connected as far as branding goes - it's all the same from a customer's perspective. I did also leave this review on yelp and have seen other reviews cross-posted in both places as well (about the online shop and the location).

Either way, I was not confused, I was mislead. On the website, the summer color listings had "pre-order" in the title until June 14th, which would lead anyone to believe they would get their skates just like any other pre-order up until that date. Moxi should've been much clearer about what a pre-order means for a small business with handmade items, as it is not common knowledge. They could've done that in a number of ways (ex. through social media, in the description of the listing, etc.), so there is no excuse. Thank you.</Review>

Jinliang Chen<//name>
<Date>1560577116344</Date>< rate>
5<//rate>
< Review>
For flavors, it‚Äôs not your typical American Chinese restaurant. For interior design and service quality, it‚Äôs not a San Gabriel Valley Chinese restaurant. For food variety, it‚Äôs not just a dim sum spot that only has alluring food cart running around. It does not serve over spicy Sichuan food that make you sweaty throughout the rest of the meal.

For the most part, the food is authentic. I tried the dry pot which has the right amount of spice. The twice cooked pork is still somehow sweet. But I am fine with that since it‚Äôs still delicious. The dim sum is BIG and tasty. The green tea tiramisu is liked by everyone.

Haven‚Äôt found any Chinese restaurant that house itself in a warehouse. The exposed wood frame smartly relates to the traditional Chinese wood structure system. The nice space divider with Chinese brush painting on it, the peach decoration around the steel column, the golden lotus wall art and the panda chopstick stand. All are elegant Chinese symbols that make you feel you are a distinguished guest being invited by a royal Chinese family. Besides the good service experience we had. (The gentleman in the second picture is awesome)<//Review>

I was in the mood for Chinese food, since it's been a long LONG time.

I used to live on the westside and would frequent the downtown Culver City area. Many restaurants have come and go over the years, and I remember this space being a different restaurant.
Painfully so - but he has good intentions. He found this place, and off we went.

Now - we were there on a Tuesday evening, and it was RAINING (nay, POURING with thunder/lightening) - so it was a little empty. Completely understandable. So service was great - since no one was there. I'm sure the service is on par on other busy nights too - but I cannot speak to busy times.

We were both starving - so we ordered WAY too much. Fret not - I took the leftovers and they heated up nicely. :)

We ordered the Scallop app, the Fifty One noodle dish, and a bunch of different Dim Sum.

Everything came out when ready - and it was fast and furious (again, being that it was rainy Tuesday night).

The only thing that was a little limited was the drink menu. I'm not much of a drinker in the first place, so that's not much of a problem.

This place is worth checking out. It's reasonably priced, and it'll save you the time to driving to the SGV for good Chinese food.< /Review><Resp>None< /Resp>< date>

Dexter Hollier-Larousse< /name>
<Date>1551415019186<//Date><Rate>3<//Rate>< review>
Food was tasty and in great quantity. Be sure to ask for their in-house soy sauce, and I recommend the sesame balls for desert.
The 3-star rating is for one reason:
1) DO NOT get the duck. Comes in a vat of broth which is cool, but it's big and you have to stand up in order to get any food. Also, you have nowhere to put the bones when you are done, and there is no real way to cut the meat from the breast as they don't provide a knife. Ended up making a mess on the table. There is no true taste on its own, but the in-house soy sauce makes up for it.
Aside from the duck, a good place to eat!< /review>

< UserId.>
109638664791163963925</UserId.>
<Name>Jen Evenger</Name><Time>1571245325504</Time><Rate>4< /Rate>< Text>
Parents were in town and, craving Chinese, picked this spot. We'll start with how they're notoriously high maintenance so kudos first to the staff who were all kind and accommodating (not to mention surprisingly young/diverse/attractive,) especially given we had 2 kids in tow. Final verdict? Good for Chinese-fusion-esque sort of cuisine. And the prices really are pretty reasonable. It's also really inside, a little oasis of sorts.

It's in the heart of downtown Culver City; not sure how I've missed it right next to Rush Street all this time but all in all, I was satisfied. We tried multiple dishes on the menu. Dim Sum was actually tasty, and are available for dinner: prepare for large versions of Har Gow (shrimp dumplings) and Shumai (your choice of chicken or pork), and the Xiao Long Bao (soup dumplings) were actually decent.

Some interesting renditions of some dishes: Orange Chicken is served 'deconstructed' - fried slices of chicken (like chicken katsu) with the orange dip on the side. Chicken soup served with chicken on the bone on the side. The sauteed shrimp in tea leaves was one of my favorites. Even the desserts were good - sesame balls were authentic, fried coconut eggroll was warm, crispy, and hit the spot.

For just over $200 we fed 5 adults and 2 kids and had plenty of leftovers.

Only gripes? 1) They explicitly state on the menu (even the one published online) that they give 10% off your bill if you leave a 5 star review on yelp or google. Not a fan of high ratings solicitors. 2) The charge for tea was high for what it was. $6 a pot and not like you had a choice of what kind of tea. Because we thought we were making a generic ask like in authentic Chinese restaurants, we thought it was complimentary - oops.< /Text>

<name>Ada Lim<//name><pics>None</pics><Gmap_id>0x80c2bb7f75c9ac55:0x43650e3b8f6e7d3d</Gmap_id><Review>Came here on a weekend around lunchtime and the place wasn't too busy. The restaurant is spacious and the decor is beautiful.

We ordered a variety of dim sum dishes along with a couple of other dishes off the regular menu. The vegetarian dim sum wasn't so great; we had potstickers and egg rolls that were too oily, and the potstickers barely had any filling inside. My favorite item that was actually worth the price was the jumbo pork xiu mai--it was definitely jumbo sized and quite filling! I also liked the spare ribs and the way they served it over rice. I'm a huge xiao long bao fan, so I'm pretty critical of XLBs everywhere I go. The XLB here is quite juicy, but the skin is too thick and all the dumplings were stuck together when they served it (making the skin break and all the juice spill out). We also tried the garlic lobster glass noodles, which tasted delicious but was overpriced considering the small portion size.

Service was good. The staff was very friendly and checked on us every now and then. Even though they mentioned that some dishes would require a bit of time to prepare, everything came out pretty quickly.

Overall, the food here tastes decent but is overpriced. However, this is a good spot for dim sum when I don't feel like driving out to SGV.< /Review></record></dataset><record>

<UserId.>115525113560206764538</UserId.>< name>
Kevin Kou< /name>
< time>
1549608035655< /time>
<Rating>5< /Rating><Text>Surprisingly, this place was pretty good! I grew up in a Chinese household and have had traditional shanghainese/cantonese food my whole life, and I really didn't expect this place to be authentic because it's in such a hip part of Culver next to the Arclight theater.

The dishes came in larger than expected portions and it never felt like they sacrificed quality for volume. The dry-pot dish is a specialty as is the tea-leaf shrimp. It's really cool that this place pulls dishes from different regions across China and pays homage to the regions by referencing them in the menu for people who are curious. Would recommend coming in groups of 4+ to have a good variety of food family-style.

Honestly, I'd bring my Asian parents here for a family meal and I'd be confident they wouldn't complain about the authenticity. It's not at all the same experience as going to a 626 seafood banquet hall - it's tastefully modern and smartly approachable for non-Asians. The whole place was spacious with tall ceilings and it's great for dates, gatherings, or family time. I even saw a banquet-ish table at the back which could probably fit a dozen of people and was semi-walled off with a wooden panel.

DEFINITELY make a reservation if you can, the place does get crowded and wait times can be 30+ during normal peak hours.

4.5 stars, but I'm rounding up because I want to see more authentic Chinese places in the west side.< /Text>< pics>

They pitch their tents and cooking appliance on the SouthEastern corner of Balboa and Northoff on a corner of the Mobil Gas Station (Balboa side)

The Brick Burger consist of 2 Patties, they flattened them so the patties overflow from the buns, they normally come with cheese but I don‚Äôt like cheese so you won‚Äôt see it in the pictures, I ordered their 2 burgers for $11 special, I also ordered their tater tots for $6, you will get approx 31pcs per order,

The burgers we good and tater tots was nice and crispy, I just wish they were cheaperüòú

There were 2 People working (cook and cashier, they were pretty nice

<UserId.>112427237682604984265< /UserId.><Name>Stephen Cheevers<//Name><time>1548785279171<//time>< rate>
5</rate>
<Review>Visited recently on a work trip with some colleagues, dropping by just as it was getting dark. We took a table outside in the alley (much nicer than it sounds) and started off with drinks. The drinks were good, price was reasonable. Food is standard Irish pub food, good quality. Our waitress helped me acquire some curried chips which was a nice touch.

Overall, it's a good bar/restaurant, serving good quality food and they don't cheat on the drinks either, or water them down as far as we could tell. And we conducted a thorough test. Definitely recommended for an evening, or to drop in after work.

Pro tip: The bouncer/assistant/maitre'd who greets you when you walk up and helps you get a seat, looks EXACTLY like a customer so we didn't recognize at first that he worked there and tried to walk past him. But he was a good guy and fine about it.<//Review><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMN01mFVNpPxrESeh_ZN_MwclsfKrKHe9rHYjhI=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pictures><response>None</response>< gmap_id>

I had been wanting to go to the Irish Bank for a while and finally had the perfect excuse. Very authentic old Irish pub in the middle of SF. The bar was impressive with all sorts of beers, bourbon, whiskey and more. I really liked how casual it is and the friendly environment. 114541122072808793828< /user>
< text>
A hip and up and coming place, with a long history, that is great for an intimate date or a young crowd.  It could be a very romantic place, but the atmosphere was more robust and energetic (as you would expect in an Irish pub).  Our waitress was sociable and the meals a decent size.  Some cool 80's music was playing in the background and noise from the TV's in the bar were audible; a pleasurable experience so much better than the typically dead atmospheres of other restaurants I've been in. A hidden gem in San Fransisco. 5 stars.</text>

< review>
Irish Bank is a good solid bar in the Financial District.  Drinks here a priced moderately, with most people drinking beer or Irish Whiskies.  The outside patio is nice when its nice out, and there is a back room that has more tables as the main room gets too crowded.  Super fun on St. Patrick's day as they have a giant party here.  Also fun for Happy Hours.  It's a bit old and has that old bar smell.<//review>

I will not be going here any longer and I will convince my coworkers to visit other establishments from now on. The staff was "totally cool" but less than accommodating.

I arrived here with about 6 of my coworkers and more showed up throughout the night. The staff was unwilling to serve me at the bar due to the "table service" we didnt even want. We wanted to buy drinks at the bar and sit and chat at a table like every other bar in the city... No one was even ordering food... we sat in the outside patio and had a few drinks. I guess for them that meant one large tab instead of people ordering their own drinks individually.

I asked if i could instead pay for just the drinks I ordered. No, I must pay the tab of the other members who were still there enjoying themselves.

... The waitress told me to go get cash from my table.

< UserId.>
101419110504188939778</UserId.>
< username>
Justin Ryan</username>
<Date>1533931679262<//Date>< Rating>
1< /Rating>
< Review>
A wonderful place if you want to get physically assaulted by staff.

Went here for dinner. Got a hamburger and two beers. Prices were a bit high, service a bit tame, but nothing terrible.

Came back later for late night drinks around 10 pm or so. Bought a $7 beer with a 10 dollar bill. Immediately after I purchased, went to put in a couple of bucks in the jukebox machine to hear some good tunes. When I came back, change from my beer was missing despite my being gone for less than a minute. Every bar I've been to, from SF to LA to Europe to Asia, has my change waiting for me after I order a drink.

Not the Irish Bank, apparently.

I called out the bartender on it. He told me I disappeared, despite me going to the jukebox literally right around the corner in plain eyesight. We get into a back and forth, he becoming faux defensive about me using the F-word. He gets my change from the tip jar for some reason instead of the cash register, further implying he never thought I was coming back and wanted to pocket the money. We get into a verbal altercation, I throw a beer in his face, and I get kicked out.

I know, immature move on my part. But i thought that was the end of it. I was wrong.

I sit outside a block up from the bar, smoking a cigarette about 15 minutes after the encounter. Bartender from earlier walks up and asks me if I'm the same guy, I say yeah. He starts throwing wild punches at me and kicks me repeatedly. I try to defend myself but he's vicious, throwing everything he's got at me. Bystanders witness the whole thing and cops get called, bartender runs off into the night. I spend 30 minutes filing a police report, officers constantly asking if I want to go to a hospital or emergency room to take care of my black eye and busted lip. I say no, I can take care of it on my own. They ask me if I intend on pressing charges, I say yes.

There's a lot of bars in San Francisco, and a lot in this nearby area. Don't waste your time on the Irish Bank. You'll either get overcharged for a beer or will get physically assaulted from staff. Unless your Muhammad Ali or Ronda Rousey, it isn't worth it to come here to deal with the fights. Attached is a photo of my black eye, courtesy of The Irish Bank.< /Review>

< Name>
D. M.</Name>
<gmapID>0x8085808970c3e43b:0xe17d380c1e7aede8< /gmapID>< review>
This is my first Google review. Sat down for a beer on the patio on a beautiful day. A patron sitting in the patio (a regular, based on how all of the wait staff treated him) lit up a cigarette, no more than 10 feet from the door, and smoked it brazenly, blowing smoke into the patio area as if he were smoking a cigar.

After a woman had to move closer to me, saying that she could not tolerate the smoke either (and also would not be able to eat nor bring her daughters to eat as she had planned), I went inside to ask a server to ask that they request the patron extinguish it. They made a cursory attempt to ask the regular to extinguish it, although he just held it under the table for the remainder of the cigarette.

As the woman could no longer handle the smoke still wafting into the patio area, she left abruptly. I moved to the only other open outdoor table -- seating for 10 or so. I sat at the very end. This was approximately 5pm on a beautiful Friday. While I was finishing my beer, a line formed for the patio, and I saw a number of groups leave in vain because there were no longer any "free" tables.

10 minutes later, when the man lit a second cigarette, I asked the waiter if they were going to enforce the smoking ban on the patio. The waiter said he "just got there" and did nothing. When I still smelled the smoke, this time from across the patio, I finally went inside, despite wanting to enjoy the fresh air of a beautiful day. I asked the manager (owner?) the policy for smoking on the patio. He said smoking it is "at your own risk", despite having signs prominently posted that say no smoking within 25 feet of any entrance (city law). I asked for clarification, and he said that if smokers get caught, that it's up to them to deal with the consequences. I asked if that meant the establishment makes any effort to operate consistent with city law, and he said (rather rudely) that "if we try to get them to put it out, then they just go into the alley and smoke anyway". When I pointed out that that would be perfectly legal and reasonable, so long they were removed from the entrance/patio area, he just walked away. I would not have taken the time to write this if it were not for the utter indifference and rudeness of this manager (owner)?

I would ask this restaurant, why do you condone your patrons breaking the law? Would you serve an inebriated person more alcohol "at their own risk"? What about the risk to the other patrons and employees who have to breathe carcinogenic smoke while they simply wish eat and drink?

IN SUMMARY, avoid this patio if you do not wish to have smoke blown in your face. Avoid the indoors of this establishment if the doors are open and you do not wish to smell smoke.</review>

<user>115549233281429989081<//user>< Name>
Eireann Emerald<//Name>
< date>
1536483695096<//date>
<Rate>1</Rate><Review>This place is MUCH different than described in the online reviews.  I hoped it would become my new Irish social spot. (If you were a patron of Joxer Dalys at West Portal and Durty Nellies on Irvine St., you will recall the friendly greeting received upon entering the bars and your favorite beer immediately brought to you by chatty, personable staff who always acted happy to see you.) What I found was a small, somewhat dark, antiquated, interior with a bar wrapped around a wall, some old tables and chairs in the middle of the floor, and a few large beer barrels in the corner surrounded by stools sitting against the wall.  I was not greeted by the bar staff when I entered, although there were very few patrons inside, so I sat down at a table and waited for a sever to take my order.  Suddenly, a woman rushed past me without a glance or acknowledgment; upon returning she caught my eye and quickly blurted out that I had to order at  the bar.  So, I  got up and stood in front of the bar, and without any formal greeting, one said,  "what do you want to order?"  The so-called authentic, delicious, Irish breakfast  came about 20 minutes later, tossed onto my table by the same barman, who then quickly rushed back to the bar.  As I looked down, I was shocked by the sight that greeted my eyes: Two overcooked, brownish eggs, with greasy egg whites; a burnt, tiny, shriveled piece of bacon; 2 tiny pieces of hard, overcooked white/black pudding (I couldn't tell you which was which); a small serving of (canned) baked beans and a piece of toast.  I ate it because I was starving and because my intuition told me to not waste my energy complaining about the complete lack of food quality and culinary skills in the kitchen.  I didn't want the experience to be a total loss so I decided to sit at the bar and order a beer.  One of the barman looked at me and said,  "Ready to Rock and Roll?" and then plopped my tab in front of my face. When I told him that I actually wanted to order a beer, he made a small effort to stop me but my facial expression said it all, and he left it alone, without so much as a "see you again," or "thank you for coming," as I left.  What a waste of $15.00.  Never again.  Google also recommended Chieftains Irish Bar, located on Fifth Street, for great Irish breakfast, lunch, and drinks.  I'll try them tomorrow.  Maybe they'll serve me a beer.<//Review><Pictures>None<//Pictures><Response>None</Response>< gmapID>

<Rating>4< /Rating><text>Irish restaurants seem to be highly criticized everywhere i go, making me think they are either sub-par on the west coast as a whole and i havent been exposed to anything else... or people are just stupid and snobby for no reason. as far as i can tell, this food is simple, filling, cheap, pub-style food to absorb all the alcohol you are consuming. and for me, that is just fine.

we were strolling around the area deciding on dinner, and the lovely alleyway patio caught my eye. the tables are simple no frills patio tables and the lighting is red at night...making food photography terrible btw :/

i will keep this simple like the food and experience was:

app: blue cheese fries. yum. IF you like blue cheese which is plentiful

irish beef stew: for a warm night it normally wouldnt have been my choice, but i wanted something authentic and several people spoke highly of it so i gave it a go. i liked it a lot...even with a small appetite. i would have liked it a bit chunkier with the veggies but the flavor was good.

black n tan: i just have to get it anytime im at an irish pub. well made :)

dining partner got the reuben and it looked quite tasty.

service was good...food came out quick...busser was VERY enthusiastic and diligent, it was sweet. no complains< /text><Pictures>None< /Pictures><Response>None<//Response>< gmap_id>
